reviewText: The Untouchables (Season 4): Don't believe everything you read ... there is absolutely no drop in quality regarding this last season of an absolutely CLASSIC TV series. It may possibly be considered the lesser of the 4 seasons, but the acting, production values, guest stars ... all contributed to a fantastic and worthy program ... making "The Untouchables" probably one on the BEST classic TV crime-series of all time (ranking right along side "Hawaii Five-0"). It could well be that the Desilu Studio interests began to lose concentration during this final season and began expanding their efforts into other areas. Also, there were probably not too many more stores to be told (exposed) during this brief span of the Eliot Ness chronicles (1929-1933). I would have savored a final fifth season to wrap it all up, but the TV Gods denied that. All in all ... I own all 4 season sets ... and they are at the TOP of my collectible TV favorites (which are quite numerous and varied). This was a one-of-a-kind series and it will always be that. Enjoy and embrace what you will never again experience from a time back when you never expected such greatness.

It always reminds me when I was a kid (In France the show was broadcasted in the 70's). Robert Stack will be forever Eliot Ness in my heart and my mind. RIP : a great man and a fantastic actor !

reviewText: Well, here it is. The final season of "The Untouchables".This show had  one of the longest shelf- life's of  any series despite being shot in black and white,which only lends to it's authentic feel to that era. Apart  from the Capone episodes all other stories  concerning the Untouchables are inaccurate and fictitious,although,the characters portrayed in most episodes were real.Robert Stack was perfectly cast as Eliot Ness and is the best version portrayed by any actor.Plenty of action in this series. I believe that the show was cancelled not by falling ratings but by lobbyists complaining about the amount of violence on T.V. Well this was about gangsters of the prohibition era.What did they expect. Many well known actor's had early roles in this series like Jack Lord, James MacArthur, Clu Gulager, Telly Savalas, Peter Falk,Cameron Mitchell even Barbara Stanwyck who was a big movie star at the time appeared in two episodes which can be seen in this season. It was a stroke of genius to have Walter Winchell,who was a news reporter in the thirties, narrate the series.It gave the show a sense of realism.The masterful musical theme set the mood for this series and takes me back to when I was a child sitting on my father's lap watching this show.This is a great,great,great show. A television classic.
summary: Eliot Ness: A stack above  other law enforcers

reviewText: AFTER years of viewer expectations we finally have the LAST season SEASON FOURTHE NIGHT THEY SHOT SANTA CLAUS~ a killing on Christmas Eve has Ness looking at his old police friend who has a hidden side~COOKER IN THE SKY~ ONE OF THE best~ JD CANNON is hired as a middle man who builds a NESS PROOF BREWERY on the 6th floor of a building~ ADDED fun is the former mob middle man (Martin Seltzer) plots to help NESS bring down the whole scheme.CHESS GAME: Richard Conte is a blind bootlegger who is A VERY clever man.THE ECONOMIST: THE MOB has booze supply problems to raise the profits.THE PEA: small time waitor has hope of rising in the mob.BIRD IN HAND: bird flu has a cash delivery go bad.THE EDDIE O'GARA STORY~ FIRST RATE: Eddie O'Gara plays up TO Bug Moran who is in hiding to gain power in the underworld~ Mike Connors shines~~~ELEGY: Ness strikes a deal with a dying mobster.COME AND KILL ME~ the only episode in four season written by a woman~ FIRST RATE: a mastermind is running a school for KILLERS one of the few episodes filmed off the studio lot~~A FIST OF FIVE: LEE MARVIS is excellent as a HONEST cop tossed off the force who schemes with his brothers to kidnap a mob boss for cash~~~ Marvin is outstanding.THE FLOYD GIBBONS STORY~ a reporter is KILLED on the verge of a big story break.DOUBLECROSS: NESS starts his own supply and bootlegg booze supply in order to cripple the mobs top sellers.SEARCH FOR A DEAD MAN: BARBARA STANWYCK IS AGGIE STEWART who is the head of a MISSING PERSONS unit look for ED ASNER as a her assistant as they use dental and EARLY CSI techniques to label and name a body. this was an attempt for a SPIN OFF OF THIS SERIES BUT IT DID NOT GET PICKED UP THE NETWORKS the story ties in with Ness.GREAT SEASON FOUR AFTER WHAT?? 5 YEARS AT LAST GREAT SOUND AND NEW DIGITALIZED ALL THE WAY~ FIRST RATE AND WORTH THE WAIT AND LOTS OF GREAT EARLY STARS.MOST HIGHLY RECOMMEND THIS.
summary: AT Long LAST SEASON 4~ Eliot Ness ~ GREAT~ 5 STARS

reviewText: I love the show, even though CBS/Paramount butchered seasons 2 & 3!  Season 4..... I love the show....HATE the MUSIC!  What happened here? Is this bogus music on Season 4? It's so fast and very loud and sharp like a new digital remake!?! It is very intrusive in many scenes and gets in the way of Walter Winchell's narration at times. It's like Nelson Riddle on steroids! I find it hard to believe they would have changed the original music so drastically for the 4th season in 1962! I have only watched the beginning episodes of Part OneUntouchables: The Fourth Season, Vol. 1, but I imagine Part Two will be similar. There is no mention of music substitution on the case of Part One, but on Part Two it is stated that the music may not be the music used on broadcast episodes! I may be wrong and this may be really was used for Season 4. The opening is very shoddy also! There is a sort of storybook title and a few flimsy stills of guest actors and Robert Stack. This also looks like a substitution ripoff! I don't know if any hanky panky was committed here but I would appreciate any comments and info on this by Untouchables fans!

reviewText: I'm just curious...why hasn't Steve London...who played Untouchable Jack Rossman...been on any of the covers of any Untouchables DVD case other than the First Season, Volume 1 ?After all, he was a member of the cast too....and from the very first episode, "The Empty Chair", I might add.Throughout most of the series...there were FIVE Untouchables....not FOUR. Amazon hasn't even placed his name in the cast credits.Four stars for the final season , not as good as the first 3, but it had it's moments...like the great episode , "A Taste For Pineapple" which guest-starred Jeremy Slate, co-star of the 1960-61 CBS T.V. series, The Aquanauts (this episode featured Untouchable Jack Rossman quite prominently, I might add....and yes, I KNOW it's in Vol. 2) This turned out to be, but wasn't intended to be, the series finale...ABC wanted The Untouchables to return for a fifth season...but Robert Stack , an noted Academy Award-nominated motion picture actor, was burned out on series television, and wanted to return to feature films.Oh well, at LEAST Season 4 is  FINALLY coming out.(Would have liked to see ALL 5 Untouchables on the cover , though ).
